05274nam a22008055i 9780812207095DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979954245  a97808122070957 a10.9783/97808122070952doi  a(DE-B1597)449566  a(OCoLC)806246648  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0070002bisacsh04a947.00090491 aMitchell, Lincoln A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Color Revolutions /cLincoln A. Mitchell. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Pre-Color Revolution Regimes -- tChapter 3. Electoral Breakthroughs -- tChapter 4. The U.S. Role -- tChapter 5. Russia -- tChapter 6. Democracy After the Color Revolutions -- tChapter 7. Exporting Color Revolutions -- tChapter 8. Misreading Democratic Breakthroughs: U.S. Policy After the Color Revolutions -- tChapter 9. The End of an Era -- tAppendix: Studying Color Revolutions -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom late 2003 through mid-2005, a series of peaceful street protests toppled corrupt and undemocratic regimes in Georgia, Ukraine, and Kyrgyzstan and ushered in the election of new presidents in all three nations. These movements—collectively known as the Color Revolutions—were greeted in the West as democratic breakthroughs that might thoroughly reshape the political terrain of the former Soviet Union.But as Lincoln A. Mitchell explains in The Color Revolutions, it has since become clear that these protests were as much reflections of continuity as they were moments of radical change. Not only did these movements do little to spur democratic change in other post-Soviet states, but their impact on Georgia, Ukraine, and Kyrgyzstan themselves was quite different from what was initially expected. In fact, Mitchell suggests, the Color Revolutions are best understood as phases in each nation's long post-Communist transition: significant events, to be sure, but far short of true revolutions.The Color Revolutions explores the causes and consequences of all three Color Revolutions—the Rose Revolution in Georgia, the Orange Revolution in Ukraine, and the Tulip Revolution in Kyrgyzstan—identifying both common themes and national variations. Mitchell's analysis also addresses the role of American democracy promotion programs, the responses of nondemocratic regimes to the Color Revolutions, the impact of these events on U.S.-Russian relations, and the failed "revolutions" in Azerbaijan and Belarus in 2005 and 2006.At a time when the Arab Spring has raised hopes for democratic development in the Middle East, Mitchell's account of the Color Revolutions serves as a valuable reminder of the dangers of confusing dramatic moments with lasting democratic breakthroughs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aHuman Rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh  aEuropean History.  aHistory.  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.  aWorld History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Law & Political Sciencez978311041352608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220709540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812207095423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812207095.jpg 